    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:b818af14-1002-4da2-8962-6bf67dde033b",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 58-year-old male who presents to the gastroenterology clinic with a 4-month history of intermittent epigastric pain, bloating, early satiety, and occasional nausea. He describes the discomfort as a dull, burning sensation in the upper abdomen that tends to worsen after meals, particularly spicy or fatty foods, and sometimes awakens him at night. He denies hematemesis or melena but reports occasional belching and a mild loss of appetite over the past several weeks.\n\n{patientName} is a retired construction site supervisor who now spends his days tending to a modest vegetable garden, watching football, and meeting with his longtime friends at a local diner every Saturday morning. He is moderately overweight, carrying most of his extra weight around the midsection, and gets only light physical activity on most days. He is a current smoker with a 30-pack-year history and admits to drinking 2–3 glasses of whiskey most evenings to \"wind down.\"\n\nHe lives with his wife of 32 years in a single-story home in a suburban area. They have two adult children who live nearby. {patientName} tends to eat irregularly, often skipping breakfast, and has a strong preference for processed, salty, and fried foods. He drinks several cups of coffee throughout the day and frequently takes over-the-counter NSAIDs for chronic lower back pain stemming from decades of physical labor.\n\nOn physical examination, {patientName} appears mildly uncomfortable, with mild epigastric tenderness on deep palpation. He is alert and oriented, mildly flushed in complexion, with a BMI of 29.4 kg/m². Vital signs are within normal limits. His abdomen is soft without guarding or rigidity, and bowel sounds are normal in all quadrants.\n\nOverall, {patientName} presents as a middle-aged man with multiple lifestyle risk factors — smoking, alcohol use, NSAID overuse, and a high-fat diet — that have likely contributed to the development and persistence of his gastric mucosal irritation. His clinical picture is consistent with unspecified gastritis, and he is motivated to make changes after expressing concern about his long-term digestive health."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:ae908c14-5b5d-42b8-a984-cb517fa08afb",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has a background of hypertension diagnosed approximately 10 years ago, for which he is on antihypertensive therapy. He also has a history of dyslipidemia managed with a statin, and type 2 diabetes mellitus diagnosed 5 years ago, currently controlled with oral hypoglycemic agents. He was hospitalized once approximately 7 years ago for a lower respiratory tract infection that required a brief inpatient stay.\n\n{patientName} has a significant 30-pack-year smoking history and is a current smoker. He consumes alcohol regularly, averaging 2–3 standard drinks per evening. He takes over-the-counter ibuprofen frequently — often daily — for chronic lumbar back pain, a habit he has maintained for several years without gastric protection. He has no known prior episodes of gastrointestinal bleeding and has never undergone upper endoscopy before.\n\nHis surgical history includes a right inguinal hernia repair approximately 15 years ago, performed laparoscopically without complications. He has no known drug allergies on record, though he reports mild stomach upset with certain antibiotics in the past. He is up to date with routine colorectal cancer screening (last colonoscopy 3 years ago, normal). There is a family history of gastric cancer on his paternal side. His immunizations are current including annual influenza and COVID-19 booster."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
